element_texts.text: Summerville March 14, 1880 Rev Graham Taylor My dear friend Do not be surprised that I drop you this line. You preached for our people now nearly a year ago - when we were in no condition to call a minister, or in fact to deliberate previously on such a subject. Since then we have relieved ourselves from former minister (?Shane) the church is in our own hand. The acceptance with which you then preached has not since thus been forgotten. + during all the phases of our past difficulties your name has never been dropped; but on the contrary been constantly gaining strength -

element_texts.text: tho evidence of the fact as I state it. of which is a day or two you will receive further confirmation. And now I come to a part of this subject upon which I feel a delicacy to write I am a novice in such subjects if I make a mistake (......) looking only at the motive. There are summons you have received a call (..) to an other people or other (....) + while I have no right to feel it to interrogate you on this (..). I could not think it far amiss to express the hope you would delay a few days to hear from our  people on this to us most important subject. Truly yours Dumont (...).
